    <h1>Downloading My Favorite Albums</h1>
    
    <h2>Download R and RStudio</h2>
    <p>My favorite album runs on the programming language R, and the primary workspace for it is RStudio.</p>
    <p>If you don't have RStudio installed yet, the official download is <a target="_blank" rel="RStudio download" href="https://posit.co/downloads/">here.</a></p>
    <p>From the RStudio page, download R too.</p>
    <div class="note">Make sure to not download the RStudio Server</div>

    <h2>Download My Favorite Albums</h2>
    <p>To download My Favorite Albums, you need to:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Open the <a target="_blank" rel="MFA download" href="https://github.com/UW-Example-Student/MyFavoriteAlbums">official My Favorite Albums GitHub repository.</a>
        <ul>
          <li>This is where all of the code for the example website is stored.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Click the green <> Code button.</li>
      <li>Click Download ZIP.</li>
      <li>Extract the file.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>You can now run any file in the folder using RStudio.</p>

    <h2>Set up RStudio for My Favorite Albums</h2>
    <p>If this is your first time using RStudio, you're likely missing some key packages My Favorite Albums requires to work. Thankfully, downloading them is very straightforward:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Open app.R using RStudio</li>
      <li>
        At the top of the left half of RStudio, there should be a yellow warning stating you are missing packages. Click Install located to the right of the warning text.
        <ul>
          <li>If not, at the top of the left half of RStudio, click Run App.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>In RStudio, open compare_bands.R, which requires another library. Repeat step 2.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Now, if you go back to app.R and click Rup App, a copy of the example My Favorite Albums site should open.</p>
  </body>
